‚∏ª
Core Evaluation Metrics:
1. Precision - Measures how many of the retrieved documents are actually relevant to the query.
(Formula: Relevant Retrieved Docs / Total Retrieved Docs)
2. Recall - Measures how many of the relevant documents were actually retrieved.
(Formula: Relevant Retrieved Docs / Total Relevant Docs)
3. F1 Score - Harmonic mean of precision and recall. It balances both metrics into a single score.
(Formula: 2 * (Precision * Recall) / (Precision + Recall) ) 

Generation-Focused Metrics:
4. Claim Recall - Measures how many factual claims made in the answer are supported by retrieved documents. High value indicates fewer hallucinations.
5. Context Precision - Measures how much of the content used in th

description:
LIVE FROM HACKING AGENTS ü§ñ‚ú®

Join Rachel Lee Nabors, head of developer relations at AgentQL by TinyQL, for a fascinating look at the future of the internet. 
 
In ten years, Internet Browsers may be a nostalgic memory. As enterprises face mounting API costs and integration headaches, a new paradigm is emerging. The internet's evolution from an open highway into a maze of walled gardens and monetized APIs has created significant challenges for businesses‚Äîbut it has also set the stage for accessing and organizing the world‚Äôs information.

This lightning talk traces our journey from the invention of the browser to the arms race of scraping for data and access to it to the dawn of AI agents, showing how the challenges of today opened the door to tomorrow. See how technologies refined by the web scraping community are combining with large language models to create practical alternatives to costly API integrations.

From the rise of platform monopolies to the emergence of AI agents, this timeline-based exploration will help you understand where we've been, where we are, and where we're heading. Join us for a glimpse of how AI agents are enabling a return to the era of free information with "the web as the API.‚Äù

description:
LIVE FROM HACKING AGENTS ü§ñ‚ú® 

2024 marked a significant breakthrough in Generative AI, demonstrating that higher accuracy could be achieved by producing more tokens during inference or test-time. This approach, while promising, unveiled new challenges: increased inference costs and slower response times. As we continue to push the boundaries of test-time compute, it's becoming evident that a balance between accuracy and efficiency is crucial for the next phase of AI development: agentic ai.

Moving into 2025, agents are poised to take center stage in AI applications, necessitating faster test-time compute on a diverse set of smaller language models (SLMs). Traditional GPU infrastructure is reaching its limits in efficiently supporting and scaling these agentic applications. This is where SambaNova's RDU architecture emerges as a solution, offering a faster and more efficient alternative for deploying Large Language Models (LLMs). This lightning talk will explore how SambaNova is empowering developers to build faster agentic applications, featuring a case study that underscores the critical need for accelerated agent inference in real-world scenarios.

description:
In this livestream, we explore advanced techniques for improving RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) performance, focusing on the nuances between similarity and relevance in AI-driven information retrieval.

This presentation is tailored for:
- Developers and researchers working on generative AI projects with RAG
- Information retrieval specialists aiming to enhance system accuracy
- Software engineers interested in optimizing RAG performance for their applications

Our discussion covers the following key areas:

1. RAG Fundamentals: An overview of RAG system architecture, emphasizing its text chunk retrieval mechanisms and integration with large language models (LLMs).

2. Defining Relevance: An exploration of relevance in the context of RAG, highlighting its crucial role in providing accurate answers to user queries.

3. Similarity in Information Retrieval: An examination of semantic search strategies, discussing both their strengths and limitations in identifying pertinent information for AI applications.

4. Case Studies: Analysis of real-world scenarios where similarity-based retrieval falls short, and how to address these challenges using advanced techniques.

5. Optimization Strategies: A discussion of cutting-edge methods to enhance RAG accuracy, including sub-query generation, entity recognition, and state-of-the-art retrieval models.

6. Integrated Approaches: An overview of how RAG can be effectively combined with content-based retrieval and hybrid search methodologies to improve result quality in AI systems.

Join us for an in-depth exploration of RAG systems and their potential for advancing information retrieval in artificial intelligence applications.

As AI applications continue to evolve, managing and querying complex data has become a challenge. That‚Äôs where vector databases come in. But what exactly is a vector database, and why should you care? Join our livestream to find out! We‚Äôll break down embeddings, how vector databases help with everything from natural language processing to recommendation systems, and how to make AI projects responses more relevant.

We‚Äôll also dive into Astra DB, DataStax‚Äôs own scalable, high-performance vector database. You‚Äôll see how it fits into your current workflow and why it‚Äôs a game-changer for building AI-driven apps without the headache of managing infrastructure.

What you‚Äôll learn:
--What a vector database is and why it matters for AI development
--How to use vector databases in real-world projects
--Why Astra DB makes working with vector databases easier
--Steps to get started with Astra and boost your AI projects

description:
Unstructured data holds immense potential, especially for Generative Al applications such as Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG).However, the diverse array of unstructured file types and sources presents unique preprocessing challenges that are difficult to accommodate for with traditional ETL. In this talk from RAG++ NYC, Maria Khalusova, a developer advocate at Unstructured, introduces the Unstructured Serverless API, which preprocesses data from 25 different unstructured file types such as PDFs, PowerPoint presentations, markdown files, and emails. She explains how to extract textual data and metadata from these formats into a standardized JSON structure. You'll also learn how to orchestrate and scale batch data processing from over 20 storage sources using Unstructured Ingest, and seamlessly integrate the results into your preferred vector database. By the end, you'll understand how to optimize data preprocessing for better use of unstructured data in RAG applications.

description:
If you're a DataStax Enterprise user or looking for a more robust cloud-native Apache Cassandra¬Æ experience, this is an event you can't afford to miss. As the cloud-native infrastructure continues to gain traction, with 84% of organizations leveraging Kubernetes, DataStax is at the forefront of this movement with innovative solutions like K8ssandra and DataStax Astra. Hyper-Converged Database (HCD) is a self-managed option that encapsulates our extensive experience with cloud-native technology.

This workshop is your ticket to mastering HCD, from initial setup to managing Cassandra workloads and exploring advanced features like the Data API and Vector Search for Generative AI applications. Discover how HCD differentiates from DataStax Enterprise and why it represents the future of your cloud-native data infrastructure. Learn to harness the power of scalability, elasticity, self-healing, and observability with HCD, ensuring your applications stay ahead of the curve.

Join us and take the first step towards a more efficient and cloud-native Cassandra experience!

--How to set up and deploy your first HCD cluster with Mission Control
--Managing and optimizing Cassandra workloads with HCD

description:
By now you've probably experienced generative AI in the form of text. Ask ChatGPT a question, get an answer. But what if you could ask about the weather and your web application could show you the current weather and 10-day forecast as an image? What if you could ask it to play Pacman?

Join DataStax and Vercel for a 45-minute livestream where we‚Äôll learn about the Vercel AI SDK and how it enables developers to deliver generative UI experiences using LLMs and React Server Components. 

During this livestream, we'll roll up our sleeves and walk through:
--Creating a new Next.js project with the Vercel AI SDK
--Generate some UI components with the help of OpenAI
--Wire it up to Astra DB to inject real data in our components

To wrap up, we‚Äôll host a live Q&A where you can ask technical questions. If you can‚Äôt join live, register anyway! We‚Äôll share the replay afterward.

description:
Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) has taken the generative AI world by storm. By combining vector databases and large language models, RAG has become the de facto way to search and navigate enterprise data for generative AI. Watch Douwe Kiela, the inventor of retrieval augmentation, in a fireside chat with DataStax to discuss the origins of RAG, and where it is going. We cover specific advanced topics such as multimodal models and fine-tuning with RAG. 

We explore Gen AI hot topics like:

Where did RAG come from and what‚Äôs next
Multimodal models and fine-tuning with RAG
Foundation models and the success over at Contextual AI

- Multi-region deployments and disaster-tolerance capabilities

description:
An introduction to durable execution and how Temporal implements it using
Cassandra. Durable execution transparently persists each step of a program so
that if the machine running the code crashes, another machine can continue
executing at the next step. It also has built-in durable timers and automatic
retries for anything that might fail. Combined, it makes it simple for developers
to write reliable code.
Loren Sands-Ramshaw | Temporal

description:
We have all dreamed of building a viral app, and now is your chance to build one! We will show you how to build a clone of the Netflix Homepage in React, how to interact with the database using GraphQL, and how to implement features such as infinite scroll and paging.

You will be guided through the process step by step, and the best thing is that you won't have to install anything - DataStax provides a cloud database-as-a-service that you can use for free with no credit card required. 

Session details:
- Create your free NoSQL database
- Learn about graphQL and create your data model
- Insert the dataset visually still using graphQL
- Deploy your application to production with Netlify
- Finally, celebrate with your new Netflix clone!

description:
7 minutes with David Dieruf, who will show you how to enable CDC for Astra DB, configure it to watch a Cassandra table on the Astra DB database, and then automatically propagate that change via Astra Streaming, built on Apache Pulsar, to another table on Astra DB.  Of course, CDC can be configured to watch Cassandra tables and propagate changes to other DBs like PostGres, Elasticsearch, SnowFlake and more.

Learn more: https://docs.datastax.com/en/streaming/astra-streaming/developing/astream-cdc.html

description:
The DataStax Astra DB command-line interface (Astra CLI) is a set of commands used to create and manage Astra resources. The Astra CLI is available across Astra DB services and is designed to get you working quickly with Astra, with an emphasis on automation.  It provides a single command line interface for Astra DB administration, CQL Querying with CQLSH, the DSBulk Data Loader, and pulsar-shell for cluster management, messaging, and more for Astra Streaming. 
Install with cURL: curl -Ls "https://dtsx.io/get-astra-cli" | bash
Install with homebrew: brew install datastax/astra-cli/astra-cli
Overview blog: https://www.datastax.com/blog/introducing-cassandra-astra-cli
Docs: https://awesome-astra.github.io/docs/pages/astra/astra-cli/
Github: https://github.com/datastax/astra-cli

From high-performance, cloud-friendly Web APIs like gRPC and GraphQL to productive APIs like REST, and a schemaless JSON Document API, Stargate has your use case covered.  Featuring awesome community member Khushi Sharma!

description:
Apache Pulsar can be deployed on cloud provider-managed Kubernetes services with ease. However, one will quickly realize that the out-of-the-box performance is not optimal for high-volume use cases. This talk won't provide cookbook recipes for tuning Pulsar instead, you will learn a systematic approach to performance tuning. The high-level mental model of the Pulsar write and read path is explained, since this helps to understand what needs to be tuned. The tunable configuration is covered at a high level. Different options for horizontal and vertical scaling of Pulsar deployments are also covered. If you are interested in learning more about Apache Pulsar operations and performance tuning, join Lari Hotari to learn about this fascinating topic.

00:00 - Introduction
01:23 - Performance Tuning
06:41 - Apache Pulsar Kubernetes deployments
23:34 - Scaling out and scaling up
27:49 - Overview of tunable configuration

*This talk was originally done at ApacheCon 2022 by Lari Hotari. It has been re-recorded for your viewing pleasure.

Connect with Lari -
Lari is the coach of the SRE engineering team focused on streaming, at DataStax. He's been a part of open-source projects for many years and is a committer & PMC member of the Apache Pulsar project.
Twitter: https://twitter.com/lhotari

description:
Download: 
https://github.com/datastax/vault-plugin-secrets-datastax-astra
Docs: https://github.com/datastax/vault-plugin-secrets-datastax-astra/blob/main/docs/index.md

With the Astra DB Plugin for HashiCorp Vault, application token management can be delegated to HashiCorp Vault, which allows associating metadata with tokens and helps track creation, rotation and revocation of the tokens, and logs token ownership and usage. It is also now possible to create dynamic tokens and lease them for a limited period of time. This allows additional security controls for Astra DB tokens and enhances the security posture for Astra DB.

Note that to use the plugin, it is required to have a functional HashiCorp Vault deployment. The HashiCorp Vault plugin for Astra DB is offered as an open source plugin and can be downloaded from here. Please refer to the technical documentation to install and use the HashiCorp Vault Plugin for Astra DB.

description:
When the Stargate GraphQL API is added to an existing Cassandra deployment, it automatically creates HTTP endpoints that expose GraphQL queries and mutations for the objects that it finds in the database. You can also create new database tables directly via the API. The built-in GraphQL Playground servlet makes it easy to prototype your mutations and queries and experiment with new approaches.

The Stargate GraphQL API comes in two "flavors":
CQL-first: you provide the CQL tables, Stargate generates the GraphQL schema. 
Schema-first: you provide a GraphQL schema, Stargate generates the tables.
In this demo we'll show both, and explain how to switch from one to the other.

Learn more: https://www.datastax.com/dev/graphql

description:
Resources and Step-by-Step for this video on Awesome Astra DB
https://awesome-astra.github.io/docs/pages/tools/integration/quine.io/

What's Quine?  Find out in this 5 min demo of an Ethereum fraud tracking example:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z8pXVof9BfE

.. or read on!  Some data needs more expressive data modeling in order to derive insights from it.  Graph databases enable richer data modeling with a simpler syntax over relational databases.  Quine has it‚Äôs roots in DARPA research and is the first in-memory streaming graph that supports real-time, event-driven workflows.  It enables high volume, low signal complex event processing like:
* Fraud detection
* Real-time recommendation engines
* Master data management (MDM)
* Network and IT operations
* Identity and access management (IAM)
Quine is a streaming graph capable of building real-time graph insights on streaming data as-is-happens, as well as for the data to be streamed-out for event processing.   The graph data is stored on disk through a configured persistent store with out-of-the-box support for Cassandra or Astra DB. When using Cassandra/Astra, Quine instances can achieve extremely high throughput, high availability, data replication, and failover strategies needed for production operation in the enterprise.

description:
In this video, Melissa Herrera shows you how to configure Temporal with Astra DB, built on Apache Cassandra.  Follow along in her blog if you prefer!
https://www.datastax.com/blog/how-to-connect-temporal-io-to-astra-db-in-just-5-easy-steps

Long-running tasks (workflows) are a great fit for serverless databases, as are most ‚Äúbursty‚Äù workloads that give infrastructure a chance to scale down (incurring no further usage costs until the next request).
Temporal Requires a database, and Astra DB, built on Apache Cassandra, offers Temporal users:
- Managed service simplicity
- Serverless pricing and autoscaling
- Secondary indexes (SAI)
- Global, multi-region active/active deployment
- Deployment to all major cloud providers

Learn more about Temporal, Cassandra and Astra DB

In this video, we‚Äôll provide an in-depth explanation of Apache Pulsar exactly once transactions. Learn more about transactions here: https://pulsar.apache.org/docs/next/txn-why. Get started with Pulsar today on DataStax Astra Streaming: https://astra.datastax.com/registerstreaming.

Just getting started with messaging transactions? This video is a great place to start! See how to consume, process, and produce messages in one atomic operation. Exactly-once processing guarantee means that A can only be marked as consumed if and only if B is successfully produced. This type of processing is quickly becoming popular with the rise of event streaming.

description:
In this video, we‚Äôll provide an in-depth explanation of Apache Pulsar‚Äôs shared subscription type. Learn more about shared subscriptions here: https://pulsar.apache.org/docs/next/concepts-messaging#subscriptions. Get started with Pulsar today on DataStax Astra Streaming: https://astra.datastax.com/registerstreaming.

We‚Äôre going to look at a feature of Pulsar called shared subscriptions. Typically in Pub/Sub a message topic has only one subscriber. Challenges arise when a flood of messages are published very quickly. That single subscriber can become overwhelmed. A shared subscription type means many consumers can subscribe to the same topic and share the workload of consuming all those messages.

Do you have any questions, tips, or ideas about Pulsar subscription types? Let us know in the comments section below!

name: 5 Minutes About Pulsar | Shared Subscriptions

description:
In this video, we‚Äôll provide an in-depth explanation of Apache Pulsar‚Äôs failover subscription type. Learn more about failover subscriptions here: https://pulsar.apache.org/docs/next/concepts-messaging#subscriptions. Get started with Pulsar today on DataStax Astra Streaming: https://astra.datastax.com/registerstreaming.

We‚Äôre going to look at a feature of Pulsar called failover subscriptions. Sometimes message consumers get backed up or crash all together. To help guard against that, you can have one or more consumers on standby, waiting to help. Setting the subscription type to failover tells Pulsar that when a primary consumer becomes unresponsive, a secondary should be promoted. 

Do you have any questions, tips, or ideas about Pulsar subscription types? Let us know in the comments section below!

description:
Are you interested in Machine and Deep Learning and want to learn more about NLP (natural language processing)? In this 2 hour workshop, you‚Äôll learn to create your own AI-based text classifier and make it easily accessible as a simple REST API.
By using a database as a cache layer, you will improve the performance of the API.

We‚Äôll assume you have working Python knowledge. From there, we build with Keras (Tensorflow), Fast API, pedantic and  Astra DB, a serverless DBaaS built on Apache Cassandra. This is an interactive workshop, so you will go through the whole process yourself with our 100% hands-on session! 

During the workshop, you will:
  - prepare the labeled dataset for model training
  - train the model to classify any input text
  - export the trained model and test it interactively
  - create your free NoSQL database for data storage
  - set up and start an API exposing the classifier as a reusable class!
  - learn how to speed up the API with DB-based caching
  - inspect how a streaming response is handled in the API

And much more!

Apache Pulsar‚Ñ¢ is a state-of-the-art messaging and event streaming platform, with modern features such as multi-tenancy, geo-replication, persistent storage, functions and many other.
Come and learn how to make your applications shine with this amazing technology, which enables real-time messaging patterns such as queueing, pub/sub or event processing.
Join the DataStax Developers as we show you how to build a simple multiplayer online real-time game based on Apache Pulsar! We will leverage modern technologies and frameworks such as WebSockets, React.js and FastAPI ... and you'll end up with your very own multiplayer game arena to invite your friends to!

description:
Our install-free Cassandra workshops touch upon how Cassandra is an ideal platform for instantaneous data access. Quarkus is a Java framework and runtime built on technologies and standards familiar to most Java developers. It's reactive at its core, boasting extremely fast boot times and low memory utilization, while providing near-instant scale-up. This is critical for JVM apps when running on high-density container platforms such as Kubernetes. It offers a great developer experience, with capabilities such as live coding, continuous testing, and so on. If you‚Äôre a Spring or Java developer/architect, this workshop is meant for you!! Even if you‚Äôre a novice Java developer you will be able to follow along and level up your skills.

While this demo won‚Äôt transform you into a power cloud-native programmer or architect overnight, you‚Äôll learn by doing and taking some baby steps towards the transition. In this session, you‚Äôll start from scratch by installing GraalVM and will learn how to hook up your Quarkus app to AstraDB and end up packaging it as a native app (goodbye JVM), all from a cloud-based IDE. You will also look at features of the platform such as hot reloading, debugging, etc., which make development a joy again!

name: Document API in Astra DB - Paging and subdocuments

description:
DataStax Astra DB uses the Stargate Document API to modify and query data stored as unstructured JSON documents in collections. Because the Document API uses schemaless data, no data modeling is required!  This short demo shows how to use the built in swagger client.
You can get the Javascript 'Collections' client for Astra from NPM ( https://www.npmjs.com/package/@astrajs/collections )
To use the Document API, you must define the namespace that will store collections. Collections store unstructured JSON documents. Documents can themselves hold multiple documents. Multiple collections are contained in a namespace, but a collection cannot be contained in multiple namespaces.
Only namespaces need to specifically created. Collections are specified when a document is inserted.

description:
In this episode, we will not only start to code an event streaming platform but will go on to build a fully integrated solution. We will discuss integration patterns with Apache Pulsar and how to deploy a Pulsar end-to-end solution integrated with Cassandra and ElasticSearch and a 3rd party REST API - we will perform data modifications in the data pipeline and send it to another system. We will also discuss different ways of connecting Pulsar to systems using Pulsar IO connector and pulsar functions. We will finish up by showing you options for deploying and monitoring your system, and will take Astra Streaming for a spin!

name: Event Streaming Series, Episode 3!

description:
In this episode, we take the next step on our journey to build scalable and efficient distributed applications! Using foundations learned in the first episode, we take a deeper dive into event streaming, learn messaging Design Patterns and apply them with writing Producers and Consumers to solve problems. In the second part of the session we will use the various messaging semantics Apache Pulsar has to offer to produce, consume and even query events with SQL, as if they were actual database rows!

description:
Alexander Dejanovski demonstrates how to install and run the K8ssandra 1.1 release, featuring the ability to do backups with Cassandra Medusa to storage managed by MinIO. For more information see: https://k8ssandra.io/blog/2021/04/09/backing-up-k8ssandra-with-minio/
